Comment: Greetings! This is my first annotated game, simply because my adversary had a high rating, so beating him became my record. Actually, as I noticed, he's not a genuine 1700 rating range type of player, because he got it by winning over others players having the 1200-1600 rating range. Anyway...He started the development with the king side knight.
When we started the game, I was at the end of the "learn how to open" phase. Back then, I responded with the same king side knight. I no longer do that... :)
Yada, yada, yada, the typical opening, continued by Bb2, Nc3 and a short castle.
Same here.
His majesty goes to a safe place.
His majesty goes to a safe place.
His majesty goes to a safe place.
His majesty goes to a safe place.
Okay, so he intends to dominate both long diagonals...
Back in the days I used to go Nc6 before c5. Nowadays I do it the other way around.
I open up my white bishop.
I open up my white bishop.
A strange move...or maybe I'm just not illuminated enough. :)
Taking control of the center.
Okay, now I get it...he's coming for my king.
So, in response, I attack it as well...:))
Nice move, it passed my attention, I'm pretty much blocked there with the traveling knight...I can't and won't go back to c6...I would look like a fool...
Blocking.
Finally, he puts his suveranity into safety.
Attacking...the wrong side, but still attacking...
Eventually, I get where I want with both the c pawn and the queen side knight.
Okay, so now he controls the entire 4th rank...so what? :)
Placing your queen on the enemy king's diagonal, especially in a "waiting, to errupt" type of attack, is always good.
